For this section, we will illustrate the concept of cross validation / Bias and Variance Trade off by using the football dataset. You can find the data set folder here:

  • football_train.csv: training set of the football dataset
  • football_test.csv: testing set of the football dataset (without true response variable - Wins)
  • football_answers.csv: true response variable for the testing set

For this post, we regard the answers to football_test as unavailabe during our model building/selection stage. We test our model’s performance by predicting the answers to football_test and comparing our prediction with the TRUE answers.

Content: (1) Simple EDA of the football dataset (2) Tricks for splitting dataset into training and testing (4) Bias Variance Trade Off (5) Introduce the package for cross validation

Splitting data into training and testing

The purpose is to create an artificial testing dataset of which we know the outcome variable. We will not use this testing data when training our model, but because we know the outcome, we can evaluate our model accuracy with this dataset. A model with smaller MSE in testing dataset is likely to perform equally well on unknown real-life data set as well.

set.seed(1234567)
samp_perc <-sample(1:nrow(train),nrow(train)*0.8,replace = F) ## we reserve 20% of data as holdoff set
training <-train[samp_perc,]
testing <- train[-samp_perc,]

Bias Variance Trade Off

We demonstrate this concept by first fitting the model using a model that is extremely likely to overfit (Classification and Regerssion Tree without Pruning) and then a model that is too simple (Linear Regression). We calculate the Variance, Bias as well as MSE respectively. Please note:

A Classification and Regression Tree is a flowchart-like structure in which each internal node represents a “test” on an attribute (e.g. whether a coin flip comes up heads or tails), each branch represents the outcome of the test, and each leaf node represents a class label (decision taken after computing all attributes). The paths from root to leaf represent classification rules and regression outcome. We will discussion the tree like structures in later posts

## R already has built in function for evaluating variance, we create our custome function for calculating bias and MSE
get_bias = function(estimate, truth) {
  mean(estimate) - truth
}

get_mse = function(estimate, truth) {
  mean((estimate - truth) ^ 2)
}

## Start off with an overfitting algorithm
library(rpart)
mod1 <- rpart(Wins~.-ID, data = training)
plot(mod1) ## we can also visualize the decision tree
text(mod1, pretty = T) ## this gives up an extensive tree without pruning, this model likely overfits

pred1 <- predict(mod1)
## Now let's try an underfitting algorithm, we try an extreme by predicting all response as the mean of the response
pred2 <- rep(mean(training$Wins), dim(training)[1])
## We choose a random observaation to test the variance and bias
set.seed(1234)
index <- sample(1:dim(training)[1],1)
get_bias(pred1[index],training$Wins[index])
## [1] -0.6315789
get_bias(pred2[index],training$Wins[index])
## [1] 1.25
var(pred1)
## [1] 7.411235
var(pred2)
## [1] 0
get_mse(pred1[index],training$Wins[index])
## [1] 0.398892
get_mse(pred2[index],training$Wins[index])
## [1] 1.5625

From this simple example, we can observe that simple models are likely to have (1) small variance (0 in our extreme case) (2) large bias and our complex model is likely to have (1) small bias (2) high variance.

Package for cross validation

library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
train.control_1 <- trainControl(method = "LOOCV") ## Leave one out cross validation
train.control_2 <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10) ## 10
mod3 <- train(Wins~.-ID, data = training, method = "rpart",
               trControl = train.control_2)
